Is unlimited PTO a Scam? ⚠️

I have my opinions, but I’ll let you form your own 👇

Unlimited PTO means you have unlimited Paid Time Off ⏰

But it might not be as good as it sounds… 🚨 

First, You can’t take unlimited days off of work, you still have a job to do and will be fired if you don’t do that job ❌

Second, Unlimted PTO always comes with fine print. Ie:
- You need to get PTO approved first 
- You can’t take PTO during the busy season 
- You can’t take PTO when others are taking PTO

It’s definitely not as unlimited as it sounds ⚠️ 

But the biggest argument I have against unlimted PTO is that you will not get paid out for the unused days. 

Traditionally if you leave a company with 3 extra days of PTO, you would get paid for 3 extra days of work ✅

But with unlimted days of PTO, the company won’t pay you anything if you leave, because there’s no limit to PTO ‼️

If you haven’t checked out @your.richbff video on Unlimted PTO, I highly recommend it! 

Just know that if it sounds too good to be true, it probably is 😬

Credit Cards in less than 60 Seconds ⏰ 

A Credit Card is borrowed money from the bank 🏦 

Whereas a Debit Card is money straight from your own bank account 👇

You must pay back your Credit Card within 30 days (also referred to as your statement balance) 📝

If you don’t pay off your statement balance within 30 days you will owe Interest 📈

Interest is money owed for borrowing money. Usually based as a percentage 💯

And Credit Card Debt has extraordinarily high interest usually 20%+ 😬

So the longer you don’t pay off your statement balance, the harder it is to get out of debt ⚠️

So my best tip for beginners is to set up automatic payments ♻️ 

So you’ll never owe interest and you’ll never go into debt ✅

4 Money Accounts Everyone Should Have 🔐 

1) Checking Account ✅

This is for day-to-day money 💵 

You get paid into your checking account and you pay bills with your checking account ✅

2) Savings Account 🙏 

This account is for money you’ll need in 5 years or less 

For example you would use a savings account to save for a houses save for a vacation, or save an emergency fund 🏡 

3) Investment Account 📈

This is for long term investing also known as a brokerage account. Ideally you should be investing money for 10+ years 🚀 

4) Retirement Account 👴

This is the account you plan to retire with. Money should stay in here for 30+ years 🙌

Is your Car Loan Underwater? 💦 find out 👇

@johnefinance @johnefinance @johnefinance 

If you bought a new car last year, your car might be “underwater” ☔️ 

Being “underwater” on a loan means that:
You owe more on the car, than the car is actually worth 😬

For example, if you bought a $40,000 Tesla last year ⚡️ 

The Tesla may only be worth $32,000 after used cars have declined and Tesla slashed its prices 📉

This means that if you wanted to sell your Tesla now 👇

You’d actually have to pay an additional $8,000 to the bank after you sold it. 🫠

Bought for $40,000
Sold for $32,000
Owe banks $8,000

If you want to check if your car loan is underwater,

Call your lender or person who sold you your car ☎️ 

Ask how much is left on the loan amount 🧾

Then compare that to the Kelly Blue Book value of your car ✅

If you ARE underwater on your loan, the best bet is to continue making payments on the car as usual 👍

But if you can’t afford the payments, you’ll likely have to get a personal loan needed to sell the car

How to Break Your Bad Habits 👊💥

Atomic Habits by @jamesclear is one of my favorite books 📚 

And the 3rd Law says in order to Build a Good Habit, you must make it easy ✅ 

Which means if you want to Break a Bad Habit, you must make it difficult ⚠️ 

I love the term “adding friction” to your bad habits 🤜🤛

For example, if your bad habit is impulse shopping on Amazon, there are multiple ways to add Friction 💥

1) You can Log Out of your Amazon account after each purchase. This will cause friction by having to enter your username and password each time 💻

2) You can remove your saved Credit Card from your account after you buy. If you have to enter your card number before each purchase, you will likely make less purchases 🙌

3) You can delete the Amazon app from your phone. Again causing friction to download the app each time you want to buy 📲

4) You can throw away your iPhone and Laptop so you’re not tempted to buy 😆 (only in extreme cases)

So if you’re trying to build a good habit, think about how you can make it Frictionless ✅

And if you want to break a bad habit, figure how you can add more Friction to it 👊

How To Calculate Your Retirement Number 👇

If you live off of $40,000 per year, you can retire with $1 Million and never run out of money 😳

If you have a family and live off of $100,000 per year, you can retire with $2.5 Million and never run out of money 😨

If you’re single and can live off of $25,000 per year, you can retire with $625,000 and never run out of money 🤯

This works because of the famous 4% rule. 

The 4% rule states that on average, your investments will return 8% per year (average historical S&P 500 returns) ♻️

And we account for 4% of inflation per year 📈

So if you’re getting 8% per year minus 4% from inflation, you can technically withdraw 4% (8-4=4) of your portfolio each year in perpetuity 🤯

So to calculate your retirement number, all you have to do is take your yearly expenses, and divide by 4%

What’s your retirement number? 👇

That helped me save over $25,000 in 1 year 🙏

Most people see purchases as “buy it once”

When in reality we should see purchases as present and future expenses 📈

So for example, if you’re thinking about buying a new car 🚗 

You could buy a $40,000 Toyota or a $40,000 BMW

But what people don’t realize is that a BMW has more expensive Insurance, Maintenance, Gas, and Depreciation 😵

So when purchasing anything (especially large purchases like house, car, pet)

Make sure you account for the FUTURE costs associated with each purchase 👀
